885
00:47:56,460 --> 00:47:57,759
Scott: Yeah, so it's basically it works.

886
00:47:57,980 --> 00:48:01,720
Scott: It's simple, but it's unreliable and can get really shaky, right?

887
00:48:02,040 --> 00:48:04,460
Scott: This synchronous mode and this asynchronous mode.

888
00:48:04,540 --> 00:48:12,680
Scott: The synchronous mode is like, look, whenever I write a file, whenever I do something, wait till that finishes before you do the next thing.

889
00:48:13,062 --> 00:48:16,300
Scott: That way, the hard drive is always in a good way, right?

890
00:48:16,340 --> 00:48:19,560
Scott: We won't like write half a file and fail to write the rest of it.

891
00:48:19,580 --> 00:48:20,960
Scott: If something happens to the network, right?

892
00:48:21,280 --> 00:48:27,320
Scott: I mean, when you have a computer with a hard drive in it, you're pretty much like going to assume, OK, serial ATA bus isn't going to fail.

893
00:48:27,421 --> 00:48:28,440
Scott: It's really reliable.

894
00:48:28,681 --> 00:48:31,460
Scott: It's basically 100 percent reliable for all intents and purposes.

895
00:48:32,001 --> 00:48:35,420
Scott: Maybe your raid card might go down, but it's not going to like flake out.

896
00:48:35,820 --> 00:48:38,460
Scott: Networks will continue to work, but get flaky.

897
00:48:38,660 --> 00:48:39,520
Scott: You might drop a packet.

898
00:48:39,640 --> 00:48:41,920
Scott: Well, what if I drop a packet when I'm sending a file over?

899
00:48:42,120 --> 00:48:43,855
Scott: Well, I hope you were in synchronous mode, right?

900
00:48:44,600 --> 00:48:47,080
Scott: Otherwise, your file is now fucked up on the other end of the line.

901
00:48:48,282 --> 00:48:53,060
Scott: Uh, but if you're in the thing with synchronous mode is that it's mad slow.

