00:52:32,540 --> 00:52:32,661
Scott: Right.

963
00:52:32,681 --> 00:52:34,559
Scott: So the main problem is on a Unix machine.

964
00:52:35,103 --> 00:52:38,460
Scott: You know, only root really has permissions to mount file systems.

965
00:52:38,900 --> 00:52:39,061
Scott: Right.

966
00:52:39,603 --> 00:52:46,580
Scott: But sometimes one user, just a regular old user, has legitimate reason to mount a file system, perhaps in their home directory.

967
00:52:46,740 --> 00:52:59,419
Scott: For example, I might SSH to another computer where I have access to files and it'll be really nice and convenient if I could mount that remote computer that I have SSH to as a local folder instead of using SCP and SFTP.

968
00:52:59,700 --> 00:53:04,763
Scott: I could just use CP and MV and all those normal file system commands by mounting that locally.

969
00:53:05,347 --> 00:53:07,160
Scott: Now, there are some permissions issues, right?

970
00:53:07,260 --> 00:53:16,560
Scott: Because if I'm mounting something with SSH locally, then my local user account needs to be the only account that has permissions on that folder.

971
00:53:17,201 --> 00:53:20,600
Scott: But on the remote machine, the permissions are totally different.

972
00:53:21,022 --> 00:53:21,263
Scott: Right.

973
00:53:21,283 --> 00:53:24,260
Scott: Because it's what are the accounts on that machine I'm SSHing to?

974
00:53:24,601 --> 00:53:25,920
Scott: Totally different from the ones I have.

975
00:53:26,341 --> 00:53:38,160
Scott: So the chmod's and the chown's and various file system things on the local machine that I'm on need to be translated and different when they're sent over the wire or received over the wire from the remote file system.

976
00:53:38,541 --> 00:53:38,701
Scott: Right.

977
00:53:39,504 --> 00:53:47,460
Scott: But basically Fuse is this kernel module and sort of user space system that allows you to do to mount almost anything.

978
00:53:47,580 --> 00:53:47,801
Scott: Right.

979
00:53:47,922 --> 00:53:53,221
Scott: You could mount like, you know, you could turn anything and turn it into a file system.

980
00:53:53,262 --> 00:54:01,620
Scott: You could have like I'm going to turn that website into a file system and you could write some sort of driver that's like, OK, you mount the website.

981
00:54:01,821 --> 00:54:09,240
Scott: And if you can't, if you you know, if you open up the file at home, then it'll you'll get the HTML for the index that HTML.

982
00:54:09,562 --> 00:54:11,640
Scott: And if you you know, it's like you can turn anything.

983
00:54:11,740 --> 00:54:24,019
Scott: It basically turns the file system into a user interface for anything because you can turn you know, you just write a file system driver that maps to any API, any any computerized thing in the world.

984
00:54:24,723 --> 00:54:35,199
Scott: You could make like a video game that was in the form of a file system where like this one file and you open it up and it gives the instructions and then you create a file and that creates an item in your inventory and stuff like that.

985
00:54:35,600 --> 00:54:39,965
Scott: And all the while that's communicating with like a database somewhere with the game data in it.

986
00:54:40,530 --> 00:54:41,519
Scott: It's totally cool.

