1019
00:56:45,742 --> 00:56:48,260
Rym: There are so many problems and things can go wrong.

1020
00:56:48,360 --> 00:56:51,639
Rym: Like if you try to log in and your home directory isn't there.

1021
00:56:52,941 --> 00:56:55,339
Rym: Linux does not handle that nearly as well as Windows does.

1022
00:56:56,180 --> 00:56:56,361
Scott: I know.

1023
00:56:56,401 --> 00:56:56,702
Scott: Right.

1024
00:56:57,645 --> 00:57:09,860
Rym: But what if we want to, you know, what if I'm like, what if I'm mounting a file system remotely because there's log files written there and I want to like have a thing that grips those log files to generate an alarm?

1025
00:57:10,401 --> 00:57:12,760
Scott: Why don't you just have the gripper run on the log file?

1026
00:57:14,240 --> 00:57:14,923
Scott: Yeah.

1027
00:57:14,943 --> 00:57:19,720
Rym: Or why don't you use syslog to send the relevant logs to all the places?

1028
00:57:20,702 --> 00:57:22,259
Rym: Why not the whole file system?

1029
00:57:22,701 --> 00:57:23,123
Scott: That's right.

1030
00:57:23,284 --> 00:57:26,140
Rym: When all you need to do is send the individual log lines that matter.

1031
00:57:26,660 --> 00:57:30,659
Rym: Syslog, in fact, will send the logs you need to the places you need them and not send all the bullshit.

1032
00:57:30,800 --> 00:57:32,000
Scott: That's how I have it set up at work.

1033
00:57:32,020 --> 00:57:37,485
Scott: I have one server and that all the other servers have syslog configured to send their logs to that one server.

1034
00:57:37,506 --> 00:57:40,964
Scott: So if I want to see logs, I go to that one server and look at the logs and you know what?

1035
00:57:41,287 --> 00:57:42,860
Scott: They're all in one big log file.

1036
00:57:42,980 --> 00:57:45,680
Scott: So it's like, oh, my God, all the varlog messages are mixed up together.

1037
00:57:45,760 --> 00:57:51,525
Scott: But actually, I can just grep and filter that down in one second to just the one machine I care about.

1038
00:57:51,768 --> 00:57:52,900
Rym: Or I go one step further.

1039
00:57:53,501 --> 00:58:00,420
Rym: The logs are written to their local systems and they're archived to, you know, with syslog to some remote system for archive purposes.

1040
00:58:00,660 --> 00:58:04,768
Rym: You know, one of the biggest problems in Linux is that the log files get gigantic because people are stupid.

1041
00:58:04,809 --> 00:58:05,740
Scott: Well, I got rotation.

1042
00:58:06,140 --> 00:58:07,279
Rym: Yeah, most people don't set that up.

