01:02:06,040 --> 01:02:06,960
Scott: I got like three computers.

1101
01:02:07,201 --> 01:02:07,423
Scott: Right.

1102
01:02:08,006 --> 01:02:10,059
Scott: And all these computers have one hard drive each.

1103
01:02:11,161 --> 01:02:13,219
Scott: Now they could just use that hard drive straight up.

1104
01:02:13,480 --> 01:02:16,860
Scott: But, you know, I want all three computers to be identical.

1105
01:02:16,980 --> 01:02:17,744
Rym: Now let's back up.

1106
01:02:17,844 --> 01:02:21,664
Rym: Let's say I'm on one computer with three hard drives and I want them to be identical.

1107
01:02:21,724 --> 01:02:23,960
Rym: Well, I make a sort of like nerd raid.

1108
01:02:24,281 --> 01:02:24,481
Rym: Yeah.

1109
01:02:24,742 --> 01:02:32,518
Rym: So DRBD is basically raid where the disks are on multiple computers and it only does mirroring.

1110
01:02:32,900 --> 01:02:33,281
Scott: That's right.

1111
01:02:33,322 --> 01:02:41,079
Scott: So I have three computers and I DRBD them all and all those computers over the network connect to the DRBD.

1112
01:02:41,820 --> 01:02:47,220
Scott: So each computer has and one thinks to itself that it has a real hard drive in it.

1113
01:02:47,280 --> 01:02:49,760
Scott: It doesn't even know that it's this network mount situation.

1114
01:02:50,404 --> 01:02:52,440
Scott: It only sees a real hard drive.

1115
01:02:52,500 --> 01:02:54,517
Scott: It doesn't understand that is networked.

1116
01:02:55,060 --> 01:02:55,161
Scott: Right.

1117
01:02:55,181 --> 01:02:58,642
Scott: I mean, on the low level, it does, but on the higher level, it just regular hard drive.

1118
01:02:59,004 --> 01:03:01,740
Scott: But that hard drive happens to be a magic network hard drive.

1119
01:03:01,820 --> 01:03:05,760
Scott: That's actually three hard drives wide on three different computers.

1120
01:03:05,861 --> 01:03:09,500
Scott: So sitting down at any one of those computers, you'll see the exact same thing.

1121
01:03:09,500 --> 01:03:13,360
Scott: And if I edit the file on one computer on computer number two, suddenly the files edited.

1122
01:03:13,500 --> 01:03:14,111
Scott: You're like, what?

1123
01:03:14,131 --> 01:03:14,539
Rym: What now?

1124
01:03:15,380 --> 01:03:18,476
Rym: What the contention for, you know, who gets to edit a file?

1125
01:03:18,496 --> 01:03:22,200
Rym: and all that stuff is handled by the file system, which has nothing to do with DRBD.

1126
01:03:22,341 --> 01:03:24,300
Rym: DRBD is just at the block level.

1127
01:03:24,840 --> 01:03:26,900
Rym: The hard drive itself is basic.

1128
01:03:27,200 --> 01:03:31,160
Rym: Think of it as like a physical replica of the actual block device.

1129
01:03:31,381 --> 01:03:32,980
Scott: It's even below the file system.

1130
01:03:33,240 --> 01:03:33,401
Scott: Right.

1131
01:03:33,462 --> 01:03:36,300
Scott: Like NFS is a networked file system.

1132
01:03:36,761 --> 01:03:36,862
Scott: Right.

