Scott: You could take a DRBD and then use NFS on that shit.

1147
01:04:04,700 --> 01:04:05,386
Scott: It totally work.

1148
01:04:05,628 --> 01:04:07,160
Rym: Now, where do I use this sort of solution?

1149
01:04:07,340 --> 01:04:08,740
Rym: Well, we talked about log files.

1150
01:04:09,041 --> 01:04:11,760
Rym: What if I'm trying to do high availability with a database?

1151
01:04:12,541 --> 01:04:18,537
Rym: And the way some databases, most databases work is that when you make a transaction, it is written to a log.

1152
01:04:19,201 --> 01:04:21,660
Rym: Some file systems do their own sort of transactional logging.

1153
01:04:21,741 --> 01:04:24,540
Rym: You know, journaling, a journalized file system.

1154
01:04:25,202 --> 01:04:28,600
Rym: So the transaction is written to this log, which is a file.

1155
01:04:29,201 --> 01:04:31,610
Rym: And then that way the database can maintain.

1156
01:04:31,751 --> 01:04:35,685
Rym: if I do a select somewhere else before that transaction that's changing.

1157
01:04:35,705 --> 01:04:40,202
Rym: the database is completed, I see the database before that transaction.

1158
01:04:40,724 --> 01:04:48,340
Rym: But if I'm doing the operations, you know, I've made my own lock, then I personally, where I'm doing the changes, will see the changes I've made.

1159
01:04:48,783 --> 01:04:51,039
Rym: And then once I commit those changes, everyone else sees them.

1160
01:04:51,561 --> 01:05:00,260
Rym: So if I want to replicate that database, I want to in real time take that transaction log and have it be on my backup server at the same time.

1161
01:05:00,380 --> 01:05:05,140
Rym: So I need very low level, perfectly reliable, like block device, DRBD style stuff.

1162
01:05:05,340 --> 01:05:07,620
